e of pervasive homophobia. Catherine Connell’s examination of the tension between the rhetoric of gay pride and the professional ethic of discretion insightfully connects and considers complicating factors, from local law and politics to gender privilege. She also describes how racialized discourses of homophobia thwart challenges to sexual injustices in schools. Written with ethnographic verve, School’s Out is essential reading for specialists and students of queer studies, gender studies, and educational politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aGender identity. 0aHomosexuality and education. 0aSexual minoritiesxEducation. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  acalifornia school system.  acareer.  aclassroom persona.  acultural studies.  adiscretion.  adiscrimination.  aeducation system.  aeducation.  aeducational policy.  aethnographic research.  agay and lesbian teachers.  agay pride.  agender privilege.  agender studies.  alabor.  algbtq community.  algbtq.  algbtqia.  apervasive homophobia.  apolitics.  aprofessional identity.  arealistic.  aschool system.  asexual identity.  asexual injustices.  asexual orientation.  asexuality.  asocial expectations.  astudents and teachers.  ateachers.  ateaching.  atexas school system.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052027822640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095980440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520959804423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520959804/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY